# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-aboriginal-english
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] From 1928, the National Broadcasting Service, as part of the federal Postmaster-General's Department, gradually took over responsibility for all the existing stations that were sponsored by public licence fees ("A" Class licences).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The outsourced Australian Broadcasting Company supplied programs from 1929.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In 1932 a commission was established, merging the original ABC company and the National Broadcasting Service.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] It is from this time that Radio National dates as a distinct network within the ABC, in which a system of program relays was developed during the subsequent decades to link stations spread across the nation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The beginnings of Radio National lie with Sydney radio station 2FC, which aired its first test broadcast on 5 December 1923 and officially went to air on 9 January 1924.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] 2FC stood for Farmer and Company, the original owner of the station before the ABC bought the station in 1937.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The ABC then rolled out a national network across the country, somewhat similar in nature to the BBC National Programme.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The first transmitters for 2FC, 5CL and 4QG were made by AWA with power of 5 kW They used a MT7A valve for the final high power RF stage and a MT7B for the modulator.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The power supply was 12,000 volts from three-phase power rectified by MR7 valves.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] 4QG commenced with a 500 Watt transmitter which continued for about 6 months until the 5 kW unit was commissioned.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The radio transmitters for 3AR and 2FC were upgraded to 10 kW in a contract let in 1938 to STC.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The transmitters were designed by Charles Strong in London, and were notable in using negative feedback to ensure a high quality flat frequency response.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The power level of 2FC and 3AR was upgraded to 50 kW in the early 1950s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The transmitters for these were housed in the same building as the Radio 1 network.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The final stage contained three parallel 3J/261E air cooled triodes running in class C amplifier at 90% efficiency.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] These were driven by a class B push-pull modulator with the same type of valves.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In the 1970s, the network's program format began to take on a more serious tone, a style which continues to this day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Art critic Peter Timms later remarked that the network is "virtually the only non-print media forum for art in this country".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In the early 1980s the broadcast footprint was extended with the construction of the first of over 300 regional FM transmitters (including community re-broadcast sites).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In 1985, the ABC renamed "Radio 2" as "Radio National".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Since 1990, all Radio National stations have had the same callsign, "RN".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] As a result of cuts in the 1996–97 budget, Radio National was hit with a reduction of a million dollars in its funding, with a significant impact on programming.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In 2008, controversial programming changes once more raised the issue of funding cuts to the public broadcaster.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Presenter Stephen Crittenden leaked confidential programming changes in an unscheduled live broadcast before the start of his show, criticising his superiors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] He was suspended for his outburst, and his unscripted comments were cut from Radio National's podcast and transcript of the program.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Religious commentator Paul Collins on crikey.com subsequently echoed Crittenden's fears.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Crittenden was reinstated in 2009 as a reporter on *Background Briefing*, after a settlement was reached.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] However, his program and the other eight programs that had been cancelled or merged were not re-instated that year.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The head of ABC Radio, Sue Howard, was dismissed in 2009.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In January 2012 Radio National was rebranded as RN, partly in recognition of the station's growing digital audience.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] RN has also been used as shorthand for the station's name by many presenters going back several years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] RN's tagline, which has changed regularly over the years, was also changed to "Your World Unfolding" to mesh with the station's new logo and visual identity.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In 2012 a new *Religion and Ethics Report* was launched, hosted by Andrew West.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The *Media Report* was also relaunched, hosted by broadcaster and former Life Matters host Richard Aedy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The *Media Report* was, however, cancelled again in 2015.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In late 2016, the new head of the ABC Michelle Guthrie defended the removal of staff and programmes from the Radio National 2017 schedule, with the scope of the new year's lineup culled due to budget cuts with consequent staff and programming reductions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In November 2024, Radio National announced new programmes and schedule designed to relaunch the station in 2025 as "the centre of big conversations and create a space where audiences can expand their worldview while engaging with the world’s best thinkers".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] This was the biggest slate of changes and the largest announcement of new programmes since the 2017 upheaval and cuts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The new programming schedule commenced on 20 January 2025.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The station also changed its logo from the previous "RN" logo to a new "Radio National" logo.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The new *Breakfast* format now included news presenter Luke Siddham Dundon, Canberra-based political correspondent Melissa Clarke and business correspondent Peter Ryan in addition to Sara.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] The program was changed to model BBC Radio 4's *Today* programme, with more serious national and international news covered, as well as live crosses to Clarke and Ryan for politics and business coverage throughout the programme.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] As part of the change to the schedule, some long-running programmes were cancelled.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Afternoon news magazine programme *RN Drive* was also axed in favour of Kelly's *Radio National Hour,* with host Andy Park now hosting the daily afternoon news and current affair show *The World Today*, previously hosted by Sara.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Economics programme *The Money*, hosted by Richard Aedy, was cancelled and replaced by new programme *The Economy, Stupid* hosted by Peter Martin.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Lifestyle and design programme *Blueprint for Living* was discontinued, with host Jonathan Green now hosting a new weekly food programme, *Every Bite*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Rural affairs news magazine programme *Australia Wide* (which previously aired at 6:30 p.m. weeknights) is no longer broadcast on Radio National, with Kelly's programme broadcasting during its previous time slot.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] *Australia Wide* is still broadcast on ABC Local Radio stations in regional areas outside capital cities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In May 2025, Radio National announced a new annual countdown called the Top 100 Books, similar to Triple J's Hottest 100.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Each year will have a different theme, with the 2025 countdown being the Top 100 Books of the 21st Century.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] In 2026, Radio National further tweaked their program schedule particularly its arts, science and global affairs programs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Radio National broadcasts national programming in subjects that include news and current affairs, the arts, social issues, science, drama and comedy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Some programs are relayed on Radio Australia, the ABC's international broadcasting service which was transmitted on shortwave until January 2017, as well as 24-hour FM stations, local relay stations and live satellite.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] All radio programs are available for live streaming over the Internet, and most (excluding drama, poetry and music) as audio-on-demand, or for download as MP3s for at least four weeks after broadcast.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Some programs are available as MP3s going back to 2005, when Radio National commenced podcasting.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abc-radio-national] Some of the following programs, listed in order of start date, are aired on both Radio National and ABC Local Radio networks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is distinct from other accents in its county, such as the one spoken in Myddfai, due to separation by the Brecon Beacons, creating a substantial communication barrier between the two localities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] It is more appropriate to associate it with neighbouring Swansea Valley, particularly the speech in northern areas (esp.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Ystalyfera and Ystradgynlais) since they are more similar to Abercraf than ones in its county.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] This could be seen from a survey where speakers could not discern the origins of the speech of Ystradgynlais and their hometown, but were able to discern Cwmtwrch with other villages in the valley.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf was entirely Welsh-speaking until World War II, when English-speaking evacuees settled in the village.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] It is a relatively young acquired dialect.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] This can be seen from generally less assimilation and elision and clear articulation unlike other accents in Powys or Swansea.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] As a more modern accent, it is restricted to the last two to three generations, with younger people being much more likely to speak it — though much of their daily life is conducted in Welsh, leading English to be taught as a second language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is non-rhotic; /r/ is only pronounced before a vowel.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Like RP, linking and intrusive R is present in the system.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] On the other hand, the vowel system varies greatly from RP, unlike its consonants, which is stable in many English accents around the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] The offsets of the fronting diphthongs are near-close [ɪ], whereas the offsets of the backing diphthongs are close [u].
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf has kept some distinctions between diphthong–monophthong pronunciations; they are shared among other south Welsh dialects such as Port Talbot.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English generally follows West Glamorgan lexical incidence patterns.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] The vowel /ə/ is not elided, thus *factory*, *mandarin*, *reference* always have three syllables, unlike many accents such as RP or even Port Talbot.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is considered to have a 'sing-song' or 'lilting' intonation due to having high amount of pitch on an unstressed post-tonic syllable, as well as pre-tonic syllables having a great degree of freedom, with a continuous rising pitch being common.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-australian] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Some identified trends of FNE dialects are ‘irregular’ pronoun use, differences in verbal inflection, and differences in rhythmic patterning.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Differences in FNE dialects can be largely attributed to the influence of the structure and traits of different Indigenous languages.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] For example, Plains Cree has fewer phonological contrasts than the English language, has no voicing contrast, and does not contain liquids or several fricatives that are found in English.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Consequently, a smaller phonetic inventory tends to be present in speakers of Plains Cree English than those who speak with a Standard Canadian English dialect.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] On another hand, Dene Suline has more phonological contrast than English, which may influence the use of linguistic features in Dene Suline English which are not present in standard Canadian English, two features in particular being creaky voice and lateralization of sibilants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] While more research is necessary to clarify the connections between FN languages, English, and FNE dialects, there is a clear relationship between the FN languages and the FNE dialects.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Influences from other languages, mainly French, are also present in shaping pidgin, creole, and FNE dialects in Canada.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] While diverse, many FNE dialects come from similar language families and these may be cross referenced once they are identified.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Additionally, there is a suggestion that FNE dialects reveal a shared cultural history, in ways which differ from that of the English and Indigenous languages present in Canada.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] The literature reveals that there are also traits present across many FNE dialects which are not attributable to transfer from any heritage language (Indigenous, English, French, or other), further confirming roles that a collective social history may have played in the formation of these dialects.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Some analyses have concluded that contemporary Indigenous Canadian English may represent the late stages of a decreolization process among peoples who historically spoke more creolized or pidginized forms of English.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Since the 1990s, the use of the "non-standard" dialects has been poorly perceived by the non-Aboriginal majority, as evidenced by mockery and discrimination.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Some features of the dialects, for example, may have led aboriginal children to be wrongly diagnosed as having a speech impairment or a learning disability.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Academics have begun to recommend that Canadian schools accept Indigenous varieties of English as valid English and as a part of Indigenous culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] Recognition of FNE dialects helps highlight and celebrate Indigenous identity in the Canadian context.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] There are relatively few written works that appear in Indigenous English dialects.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-english-in-canada] One account is Maria Campbell's book *Stories of the Road Allowance People*, a collection of Métis folktales.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-history] The journal's scope includes the areas of Australian Indigenous history and oral histories, languages, biographies, bibliographic guides and archival research.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-history] It has also brought previously unpublished manuscripts and research in the fields of Australian archaeology, anthropology, linguistics, demography, sociology, law and geography to the professional and wider public.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/aboriginal-history] A focus on cultural, political and economic history is complemented by critiques of current events of relevance to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander culture and society.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Named in honour of Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen, wife of King William IV, the city was founded in 1836 as the planned capital for a freely settled British colony in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Colonel William Light, one of Adelaide's founding fathers, designed the city centre and chose its location close to the River Torrens.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Light's design, now listed as national heritage, set out the city centre in a grid layout known as "Light's Vision", interspaced by wide boulevards and large public squares, and entirely surrounded by park lands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Colonial Adelaide was noted for its leading examples of religious freedom and progressive political reforms and became known as the "City of Churches" due to its diversity of faiths.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] It was Australia's third-most populous city until the postwar era.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Today, Adelaide is one of Australia's most visited travel destinations and hosts many festivals and sporting events, such as the Adelaide 500, Tour Down Under, Gather Round, LIV Golf Adelaide, and the Adelaide Fringe, the world's second largest annual arts festival.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide also hosts men's tennis with an ATP 250 event and women's tennis with a WTA 500 event, and will also become the new host of the Australian MotoGP Grand Prix from 2027.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city has also been renowned for its automotive industry, having been the original host of the Australian Grand Prix in the FIA Formula One World Championship from 1985 to 1995.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Other features include its food and wine industries, its coastline and hills, its large defence and manufacturing operations, and its emerging space sector, including the Australian Space Agency being headquartered there.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] With one of the world's largest foreign-born populations, Adelaide has consistently ranked within the top-ten most liveable cities globally for much of the 21st century, being named in 2021 the most liveable city in the country and third in the world.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Its aesthetic appeal has also been recognised by *Architectural Digest*, which ranked Adelaide as the most beautiful city in the world in 2024.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] As South Australia's government and commercial centre, Adelaide is the site of many governmental and financial institutions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Most of these are concentrated in the central business district along the cultural boulevards of North Terrace and King William Street.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has also been classed as a Gamma + level global city as categorised by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, with the city further linking economic regions to the worldwide economy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is connected by extensive bus, train and tram networks, all of which are operated by Adelaide Metro, with its main railway terminus at the Adelaide railway station.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city is also served by Adelaide Airport and Port Adelaide, both of which are among the busiest airports and seaports in Australia, respectively.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The amount of time Aboriginal people have been living in the area around modern-day Adelaide has been described as "millennia", "tens of thousands of years", "thousands of generations", or "innumerable generations".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] At Hallett Cove Conservation Park in Adelaide's southern suburbs, archaeological evidence of Aboriginal culture has been found dating back 40,000 years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The area was originally inhabited by the Kaurna people, one of many Aboriginal tribes in South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city and parklands area also known as *Tarndanyangga* *Tandanya*, *Tarndanya* or *Tarntanya*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The name means 'male red kangaroo rock', referring to a rock formation on the site that has now been destroyed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The surrounding area was an open, grassy plain with patches of trees and shrubs, which had been managed by hundreds of generations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Kaurna country encompassed the plains stretching north and south of Tarntanya, as well as the wooded foothills of the Mt Lofty Ranges.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The River Torrens was known as the Karrawirra Pari (Red Gum forest river).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] About 300 Kaurna populated the Adelaide area, and were referred to by the settlers as the Cowandilla.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The more than 20 local clans across the plain lived seminomadic lives, with extensive mound settlements where huts were built repeatedly over centuries and a complex social structure, including a class of sorcerers separated from regular society.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Within a few decades of European settlement of South Australia, Kaurna culture was almost completely lost, with the last speaker of Kaurna language having died in 1929.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Extensive documentation by early missionaries and other researchers has enabled a modern revival of both, which has included a commitment by local and state governments to rename or include Kaurna names for many local places.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Based on the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield about colonial reform, Robert Gouger petitioned the British government to create a new colony in Australia, resulting in the passage of the South Australia Act 1834.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Physical establishment of the colony began with the arrival of the first British colonisers in February 1836, followed by the commencement of colonial government in South Australia on 28 December 1836.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Proclaimed by the governor near The Old Gum Tree in what is now the suburb of Glenelg North, this day is annually commemorated in South Australia as Proclamation Day.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Named for Queen Adelaide, the site of the colony's capital was surveyed and laid out by Colonel William Light, the first surveyor-general of South Australia, with his own original, unique and topographically sensitive design.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was established as a planned colony of free settlers, promising civil liberties and freedom from religious persecution, based upon the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Wakefield had read accounts of Australian settlement while in prison in London for attempting to abduct an heiress, and realised that the eastern colonies suffered from a lack of available labour, due to the practice of giving land grants to all arrivals.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Wakefield's idea was for the Government to survey and sell the land at a rate that would maintain land values high enough to be unaffordable for labourers and journeymen.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Funds raised from the sale of land were to be used to bring out working-class emigrants, who would have to work hard for the monied settlers to ever afford their own land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] As a result of this policy, Adelaide does not share the convict settlement history of other Australian cities like Sydney, Brisbane and Hobart.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] As it was believed that in a colony of free settlers there would be little crime, no provision was made for a gaol in Colonel Light's 1837 plan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] But by mid-1837 the *South Australian Register* was warning of escaped convicts from New South Wales and tenders for a temporary gaol were sought.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Following a burglary, a murder, and two attempted murders in Adelaide during March 1838, Governor Hindmarsh created the South Australian Police Force (now the South Australia Police) in April 1838 under 21-year-old Henry Inman.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The first sheriff, Samuel Smart, was wounded during a robbery, and on 2 May 1838 one of the offenders, Michael Magee, became the first person to be hanged in South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] William Baker Ashton was appointed governor of the temporary gaol in 1839, and in 1840 George Strickland Kingston was commissioned to design Adelaide's new gaol.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Construction of Adelaide Gaol commenced in 1841.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early history was marked by economic uncertainty and questionable leadership.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The first governor of South Australia, John Hindmarsh, clashed frequently with others, in particular the Resident Commissioner, James Hurtle Fisher.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The rural area surrounding Adelaide was surveyed by Light in preparation to sell a total of over 405 km2 (156 sq mi) of land.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early economy started to get on its feet in 1838 with the arrival of livestock from Victoria, New South Wales and Tasmania.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Wool production provided an early basis for the South Australian economy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] By 1860, wheat farms had been established from Encounter Bay in the south to Clare in the north.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] He was criticised for his response to the Maria massacre.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Gawler was recalled and replaced by George Edward Grey in 1841.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Grey slashed public expenditure against heavy opposition, although its impact was negligible at this point: silver was discovered in Glen Osmond that year, agriculture was well underway, and other mines sprung up all over the state, aiding Adelaide's commercial development.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city exported meat, wool, wine, fruit and wheat by the time Grey left in 1845, contrasting with a low point in 1842 when one-third of Adelaide houses were abandoned.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Trade links with the rest of the Australian states were established after the Murray River was successfully navigated in 1853 by Francis Cadell, an Adelaide resident.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] South Australia became a self-governing colony in 1856 with the ratification of a new constitution by the British parliament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Secret ballots were introduced, and a bicameral parliament was elected on 9 March 1857, by which time 109,917 people lived in the province.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 1860, the Thorndon Park reservoir was opened, providing an alternative water source to the now turbid River Torrens.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Gas street lighting was implemented in 1867, the University of Adelaide was founded in 1874, the South Australian Art Gallery opened in 1881 and the Happy Valley Reservoir opened in 1896.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In the 1890s Australia was affected by a severe economic depression, ending a hectic era of land booms and tumultuous expansionism.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Financial institutions in Melbourne and banks in Sydney closed.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The national fertility rate fell and immigration was reduced to a trickle.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The value of South Australia's exports nearly halved.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Drought and poor harvests from 1884 compounded the problems, with some families leaving for Western Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was not as badly hit as the larger gold-rush cities of Sydney and Melbourne, and silver and lead discoveries at Broken Hill provided some relief.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Only one year of deficit was recorded, but the price paid was retrenchments and lean public spending.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Wine and copper were the only industries not to suffer a downturn.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was Australia's third largest city for most of the 20th century.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Electric street lighting was introduced in 1900 and electric trams were transporting passengers in 1909.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] 28,000 men were sent to fight in World War I.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Crowley examined the reports of visitors in the early 20th century, noting that "many visitors to Adelaide admired the foresighted planning of its founders", as well as pondering the riches of the young city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide enjoyed a postwar boom, entering a time of relative prosperity.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Its population grew, and it became the third most populous metropolitan area in the country, after Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Its prosperity was short-lived, with the return of droughts and the Great Depression of the 1930s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] It later returned to fortune under strong government leadership.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Secondary industries helped reduce the state's dependence on primary industries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] World War II brought industrial stimulus and diversification to Adelaide under the Playford Government, which advocated Adelaide as a safe place for manufacturing due to its less vulnerable location.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Shipbuilding was expanded at the nearby port of Whyalla.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The South Australian Government in this period built on former wartime manufacturing industries but neglected cultural facilities which meant South Australia's economy lagged behind.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] International manufacturers like Holden and Chrysler made use of these factories around the Adelaide area in suburbs like Elizabeth, completing its transformation from an agricultural service centre to a 20th-century motor city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Mannum–Adelaide pipeline brought River Murray water to Adelaide in 1955 and an airport opened at West Beach in 1955.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Flinders University and the Flinders Medical Centre were established in the 1960s at Bedford Park, south of the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Today, Flinders Medical Centre is one of the largest teaching hospitals in South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In the post-war years around the early 1960s, Adelaide was surpassed by Brisbane as Australia's third largest city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Dunstan Governments of the 1970s saw something of an Adelaide "cultural revival", establishing a wide array of social reforms.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city became noted for its progressivism as South Australia became the first Australian state or territory to decriminalise homosexuality between consenting adults in 1975.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide became a centre for the arts, building upon the biennial "Adelaide Festival of Arts" that commenced in 1960.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The State Bank collapsed in 1991 during an economic recession.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The effects lasted until 2004, when Standard & Poor's reinstated South Australia's AAA credit rating.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's tallest building, completed in 2020, is called the Adelaidean and is located at 11 Frome Street.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In the early years of the 21st century, a significant increase in the state government's spending on Adelaide's infrastructure occurred.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Rann government invested A$535 million in a major upgrade of the Adelaide Oval to enable Australian Football League to be played in the city centre and more than A$2 billion to build a new Royal Adelaide Hospital on land adjacent to the Adelaide Railway Station.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Glenelg tramline was extended through the city to Hindmarsh down to East Terrace and the suburban railway line extended south to Seaford.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Following a period of stagnation in the 1990s and 2000s, Adelaide began several major developments and redevelopments.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Convention Centre was redeveloped and expanded at a cost of A$350 million beginning in 2012.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The government invested more than A$2 billion to build a desalination plant, powered by renewable energy, as an "insurance policy" against droughts affecting Adelaide's water supply.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Festival, Fringe, and Womadelaide became annual events.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is north of the Fleurieu Peninsula, on the Adelaide Plains between the Gulf St Vincent and the relatively low-lying Mount Lofty Ranges (Mount Lofty, the highest point, is 710 metres above sea level).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city stretches 20 km (12 mi) from the coast to the foothills, and 90 km (56 mi) from Gawler at its northern extent to Sellicks Beach in the south.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city sits at an average elevation of 50 metres (160 ft) above sea level.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Mount Lofty, east of the Adelaide metropolitan region in the Adelaide Hills at an elevation of 727 metres (2,385 ft), is the tallest point of the city and in the state south of Burra.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city borders the Temperate Grassland of South Australia in the east, an endangered vegetation community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Much of Adelaide was bushland before British settlement, with some variation – sandhills, swamps and marshlands were prevalent around the coast.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The loss of the sandhills to urban development had a particularly destructive effect on the coastline due to erosion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Where practical, the government has implemented programs to rebuild and vegetate sandhills at several of Adelaide's beachside suburbs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Tennyson Dunes is the largest contiguous, tertiary dune system contained entirely within Metropolitan Adelaide, providing refuge for a variety of remnant species formerly found along the entire coastline.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Much of the original vegetation has been cleared with what is left to be found in reserves such as the Cleland National Park and Belair National Park.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] A number of creeks and rivers flow through the Adelaide region.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The largest are the Torrens and Onkaparinga catchments.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide relies on its many reservoirs for water supply with the Happy Valley Reservoir supplying around 40% and the much larger Mount Bold Reservoir 10% of Adelaide's domestic requirements respectively.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide and its surrounding area is one of the most seismically active regions in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] On 1 March 1954 at 3:40 am Adelaide experienced its largest recorded earthquake to date, with the epicentre 12 km from the city centre at Darlington, and a reported magnitude of 5.6.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Most of the Adelaide metropolitan area lies in the downthrown St Vincent Basin and its embayments, including the Adelaide Plains Sub-basin, and the Golden Grove, Noarlunga and Willunga Embayments.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] These basins contain deposits of Tertiary marine and non-marine sands and limestones, which form important aquifers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a planned city, designed by the first Surveyor-General of South Australia, Colonel William Light.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] His plan, sometimes referred to as "Light's Vision" (also the name of a statue of him on Montefiore Hill), arranged Adelaide in a grid, with five squares in the Adelaide city centre and a ring of parks, known as the Adelaide Parklands, surrounding it.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Light's selection of the location for the city was initially unpopular with the early settlers, as well as South Australia's first governor, John Hindmarsh, due to its distance from the harbour at Port Adelaide, and the lack of fresh water there.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Light successfully persisted with his choice of location against this initial opposition.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The benefits of Light's design are numerous: Adelaide has had wide multi-lane roads from its beginning, an easily navigable cardinal direction grid layout and an expansive green ring around the city centre.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] There are two sets of ring roads in Adelaide that have resulted from the original design.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The inner ring route (A21) borders the parklands, and the outer route (A3/A13/A16/A17) completely bypasses the inner city via (in clockwise order) Grand Junction Road, Hampstead Road, Ascot Avenue, Portrush Road, Cross Road and South Road.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Suburban expansion has to some extent outgrown Light's original plan.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Numerous former outlying villages and "country towns", as well as the satellite city of Elizabeth, have been enveloped by its suburban sprawl.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Expanding developments in the Adelaide Hills region led to the construction of the South Eastern Freeway to cope with growth, which has subsequently led to new developments and further improvements to that transport corridor.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Similarly, the booming development in Adelaide's South led to the construction of the Southern Expressway.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] New roads are not the only transport infrastructure developed to cope with the urban growth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The O-Bahn Busway and Adelaide Metro are examples of a unique solution to Tea Tree Gully's transport woes in the 1980s.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The development of the nearby suburb of Golden Grove in the late 1980s followed a planned approach to urban growth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In the 1960s, a Metropolitan Adelaide Transport Study Plan was proposed to cater for the future growth of the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The plan involved the construction of freeways, expressways and the upgrade of certain aspects of the public transport system.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The then premier Steele Hall approved many parts of the plan and the government went as far as purchasing land for the project.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The later Labor government elected under Don Dunstan shelved the plan, but allowed the purchased land to remain vacant, should the future need for freeways arise.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 1980, the Liberal party won government and premier David Tonkin committed his government to selling off the land acquired for the MATS plan, ensuring that even when needs changed, the construction of most MATS-proposed freeways would be impractical.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Some parts of this land have been used for transport, (e.g. the O-Bahn Busway and Southern Expressway), while most has been progressively subdivided for residential use.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 2008, the SA Government announced plans for a network of transport-oriented developments across the Adelaide metropolitan area and purchased a 10 hectare industrial site at Bowden for $52.5 million as the first of these developments.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Historically, Adelaide's suburban residential areas have been characterised by single-storey detached houses built on 1,000-square-metre (1⁄4-acre) blocks.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] A relative lack of suitable, locally available timber for construction purposes led to the early development of a brick-making industry, as well as the use of stone, for houses and other buildings.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] By 1891, 68% of houses were built of stone, 15% of timber, and 10% of brick, with brick also being widely used in stone houses for quoins, door and window surrounds, and chimneys and fireplaces.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] There is a wide variety in the styles of these houses.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Until the 1960s, most of the more substantial houses were built of red brick, though many front walls were of ornamental stone.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Then cream bricks became fashionable, and in the 1970s, deep red and brown bricks became popular.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Until the 1970s, roofs tended to be clad with (painted) corrugated iron or cement or clay tiles, usually red "terracotta".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Since then, Colorbond corrugated steel has dominated.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Up to the 1970s, most houses were of "double brick" construction on concrete footings, with timber floors laid on joists supported by "dwarf walls".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The use of precast concrete panels for floor and wall construction has also increased.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In addition to this, a significant factor in Adelaide's suburban history is the role of the South Australian Housing Trust.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city has hot, dry summers and cool winters with moderate rainfall.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Most rain falls in the winter months, leading to the suggestion that the climate be classified as a "cold monsoon".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Rainfall is unreliable, light and infrequent throughout summer, although heavy falls can occur.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The winter has fairly reliable rainfall with June being the wettest month of the year, averaging around 80 mm.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Frosts are occasional, with the most notable occurrences in 1908 and 1982.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a windy city with significant wind chill in winter, which makes the temperature seem colder than it actually is.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Snowfall in the metropolitan area is extremely rare, although light and sporadic falls in the nearby hills and at Mount Lofty occur during winter.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Dewpoints in the summer typically range from 8 to 10 °C (46 to 50 °F).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] There are usually several days in summer where the temperature reaches 40.0 °C (104.0 °F) or above.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] While conditions vary from year-to-year, a warming trend has been increasing in recent years, and with drought conditions experienced in SA in 2024−25, Adelaide has had to rely on desalination to augment its water supply.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The city features 90.6 clear days annually.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The average sea temperature ranges from 13.7 °C (56.7 °F) in August to 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) in February.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was consistently ranked in the world's 10 most liveable cities through the 2010s by The Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In June 2021, *The Economist* ranked Adelaide the third most liveable city in the world, behind Auckland and Osaka.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In June 2023, Adelaide was ranked the twelfth most liveable city in the world by the Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In December 2021, Adelaide was named the world's second National Park City, after the state government had lobbied for this title.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] It was ranked the most liveable city in Australia by the Property Council of Australia, based on surveys of residents' views of their own city, between 2010 and 2013, dropping to second place in 2014.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide, as the capital of South Australia, is the seat of the Government of South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The bicameral Parliament of South Australia consists of the lower house known as the House of Assembly and the upper house known as the Legislative Council.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] General elections are held every four years, the last being the 2022 South Australian state election.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] As Adelaide is South Australia's capital and most populous city, the State Government co-operates extensively with the City of Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 2006, the Ministry for the City of Adelaide was created to facilitate the State Government's collaboration with the Adelaide City Council and the Lord Mayor to improve Adelaide's image.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The State Parliament's Capital City Committee is also involved in the governance of the City of Adelaide, being primarily concerned with the planning of Adelaide's urban development and growth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Reflecting South Australia's status as Australia's most centralised state, Adelaide elects a substantial majority of the South Australian House of Assembly.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Of the 47 seats in the chamber, 34 seats (three-quarters of the legislature) are based in Adelaide, and two rural seats include Adelaide suburbs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide metropolitan area is divided between nineteen local government areas.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] At its centre, the City of Adelaide administers the Adelaide city centre, North Adelaide, and the surrounding Adelaide Parklands.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] It is the oldest municipal authority in Australia and was established in 1840, when Adelaide and Australia's first mayor, James Hurtle Fisher, was elected.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] From 1919 onwards, the city has had a Lord Mayor, the current being Lord Mayor *The Right Honourable* Jane Lomax-Smith.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants are known as Adelaideans.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Compared with Australia's other state capitals, Adelaide is growing at a rate similar to Sydney and Hobart (see List of cities in Australia by population).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 2024, it had a metropolitan population (including suburbs) of 1,469,163, making it Australia's fifth-largest city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] 77% of the population of South Australia are residents of the Adelaide metropolitan area, making South Australia one of the most centralised states.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Major areas of population growth in recent years have been in outer suburbs such as Mawson Lakes and Golden Grove.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants occupy 366,912 houses, 57,695 semi-detached, row terrace or town houses and 49,413 flats, units or apartments.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] About one sixth (17.1%) of the population had university qualifications.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The number of Adelaideans with vocational qualifications (such as tradespersons) fell from 62.1% of the labour force in the 1991 census to 52.4% in the 2001 census.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is aging more rapidly than other Australian capital cities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] More than a quarter (27.5%) of Adelaide's population is aged 55 years or older, in comparison to the national average of 25.6%.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has the lowest number of children (under-15-year-olds), who comprised 17.7% of the population, compared to the national average of 19.3%.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Overseas-born Adelaideans composed 31.3% of the total population at the 2021 census.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The five largest groups of overseas-born were from England (5.7%), India (3.1%), Mainland China (1.8%), Vietnam (1.2%) and Italy (1.1%).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Suburbs including Newton, Payneham and Campbelltown in the east and Torrensville, West Lakes and Fulham to the west, have large Greek and Italian communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Italian consulate is located in the western suburb of Hindmarsh.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Large Vietnamese populations are settled in the north-western suburbs of Woodville, Kilkenny, Pennington, Mansfield Park and Athol Park and also Parafield Gardens and Pooraka in Adelaide's north.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Migrants from India and Sri Lanka have settled into inner suburban areas of Adelaide including the inner northern suburbs of Blair Athol, Kilburn and Enfield and the inner southern suburbs of Plympton, Park Holme and Kurralta Park.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Suburbs such as Para Hills, Salisbury, Ingle Farm and Blair Athol in the north and Findon, West Croydon and Seaton and other Western suburbs have sizeable Afghan communities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Chinese migrants favour settling in the eastern and north eastern suburbs including Kensington Gardens, Greenacres, Modbury and Golden Grove.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Mawson Lakes has a large international student population, due to its proximity to the University of South Australia campus.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] At the 2021 census, 1.7% of Adelaide's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] At the 2016 census, 75.4% of the population spoke English at home.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The other languages most commonly spoken at home were Italian (2.1%), Standard Mandarin (2.1%), Greek (1.7%) Vietnamese (1.4%), and Cantonese (0.7%).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Kaurna language, spoken by the area's original inhabitants, had no living speakers in the middle of the 20th century, but since the 1990s there has been a sustained revival effort from academics and Kaurna elders.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was founded on a vision of religious tolerance that attracted a wide variety of religious practitioners.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] This led to it being known as *The City of Churches*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] But approximately 28% of the population expressed no religious affiliation in the 2011 Census, compared with the national average of 22.3%, making Adelaide one of Australia's least religious cities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] According to 2021 census, 39.8% of the population of Adelaide identify as Christian, with the largest denominations being Catholic (16.4%), Anglican (7.0%), Uniting Church (3.9%) and Greek Orthodox (2.4%).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Non-Christian faith communities, representing 9.5% from Adelaide's population, include Islam (2.8%), Hinduism (2.7%) and Buddhism (2.3%).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Jewish community of the city dates back to 1840.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Eight years later, 58 Jews lived in the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] A synagogue was built in 1871, when 435 Jews lived in the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Many took part in the city councils, such as Judah Moss Solomon (1852–66).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Three Jews have been elected to the position of city mayor.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 1968, the Jewish population of Adelaide numbered about 1,200; in 2001, according to the Australian census, 979 persons declared themselves to be Jewish by religion.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 2011, over 1,000 Jews were living in the city, served by an Orthodox synagogue, Adelaide Hebrew Congregation and a Reform synagogue, **Beit Shalom**, in addition to a virtual Jewish museum.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Massada College, a Jewish day school opened in the city in 1976 and closed in 2011.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Holocaust Museum and Andrew Steiner Education Centre opened in 2020.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The "Afghan" community in Australia first became established in the 1860s when camels and their Pathan, Punjabi, Baluchi and Sindhi handlers began to be used to open up settlement in the continent's arid interior.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Until eventually superseded by the advent of the railways and motor vehicles, camels played an invaluable economic and social role in transporting heavy loads of goods to and from isolated settlements and mines.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] This is acknowledged by the name of The Ghan, the passenger train operating between Adelaide, Alice Springs, and Darwin.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Central Adelaide Mosque is regarded as Australia's oldest permanent mosque; an earlier mosque at Marree in northern South Australia, dating from 1861 to 1862 and subsequently abandoned or demolished, has now been rebuilt.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] South Australia's largest employment sectors are health care and social assistance, surpassing manufacturing in SA as the largest employer since 2006–07.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 2009–10, manufacturing in SA had average annual employment of 83,700 persons compared with 103,300 for health care and social assistance.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Health care and social assistance represented nearly 13% of the state average annual employment.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Hills wine region is an iconic and viable economic region for both the state and country in terms of wine production and sale.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The retail trade is the second largest employer in SA (2009–10), with over 91,900 jobs, and 12 per cent of the state workforce.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Manufacturing, defence technology, high-tech electronic systems and research, commodity export and corresponding service industries all play a role in the SA economy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Almost half of all cars produced in Australia were made in Adelaide at the Holden Elizabeth Plant in Elizabeth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The site ceased operating in November 2017.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The collapse of the State Bank in 1992 resulted in large levels of state public debt (as much as A$4 billion).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The collapse meant that successive governments enacted lean budgets, cutting spending, which was a setback to the further economic development of the city and state.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] As of January 2026, the government has an AA+ credit rating.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The global media conglomerate News Corporation was founded in, and until 2004 incorporated in, Adelaide, and the city is still considered the Corporation's "spiritual" home by its founder, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Australia's largest oil company, Santos, prominent South Australian brewery, Coopers, and national retailer Harris Scarfe also call Adelaide their home.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] In 2018, at which time more than 80 organisations employed 800 people in the space sector in South Australia, Adelaide was chosen for the headquarters of a new Australian Space Agency.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] It is working to triple the size of the Australian space industry and create 20,000 new jobs by 2030.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is home to a large proportion of Australia's defence industries, which contribute over A$1 billion to South Australia's Gross State Product.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Others, such as Saab Systems and Raytheon, are in or near Technology Park.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] ASC Pty Ltd, is based in the industrial suburb of Osborne and is also a part of Technology Park.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] South Australia was charged with constructing Australia's *Collins*-class submarines and more recently the A$6 billion contract to construct the Royal Australian Navy's new air-warfare destroyers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] As of November 2015, Greater Adelaide had an unemployment rate of 7.4% with a youth unemployment rate of 15%.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The median weekly individual income for people aged 15 years and over was $447 per week in 2006, compared with $466 nationally.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The median family income was $1,137 per week, compared with $1,171 nationally.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's housing and living costs are substantially lower than that of other Australian cities, with housing being notably cheaper.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The median Adelaide house price is half that of Sydney and two-thirds that of Melbourne.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The three-month trend unemployment rate to March 2007 was 6.2%.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] The Northern suburbs' unemployment rate is disproportionately higher than the other regions of Adelaide at 8.3%, while the East and South are lower than the Adelaide average at 4.9% and 5.0% respectively.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Over the decade March 2001 – March 2010, Metropolitan Adelaide median house prices approximately tripled.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] 11%p.a. compounding) In the five years March 2007 – March 2012, prices increased by approx.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] March 2012 – March 2017 saw a further increase of 19% – approx.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] no longer release a median house price for the Adelaide Metropolitan area, so figures retrieved are from Dept of the Premier and Cabinet.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Each quarter, The Alternative and Direct Investment Securities Association (ADISA) publishes a list of median house sale prices by suburb and Local Government Area.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p01] Quarterly Reports for the last two years can be found on the REISA website.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Education forms an increasingly important part of the city's economy, with the South Australian Government and educational institutions attempting to position Adelaide as "Australia's education hub" and marketing it as a "Learning City".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The number of international students studying in Adelaide has increased rapidly in recent years to 30,726 in 2015, of which 1,824 were secondary school students.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the birthplace of three Nobel laureates, more than any other Australian city: physicist William Lawrence Bragg and pathologists Howard Florey and Robin Warren, all of whom completed secondary and tertiary education at St Peter's College and the University of Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also the hometown of mathematician Terence Tao.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] There are two systems of primary and secondary schools, a public system operated by the South Australian Government's Department for Education, and a private system of independent and Catholic schools.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] South Australian schools provide education under the Australian Curriculum for reception to Year 10 students.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In Years 10 to 12, students study for the South Australian Certificate of Education (SACE).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] They have the option of incorporating vocational education and training (VET) courses or a flexible learning option (FLO).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has 24 schools that use International Baccalaureate programs as an alternative to the Australian Curriculum or SACE.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] These programs include the IB Primary Years Programme, the IB Middle Years Programme, and the IB Diploma Programme.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] For South Australian students who cannot attend a traditional school, including students who live in rural or remote areas, the state government runs the Open Access College (OAC), which provides virtual teaching.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The OAC has a campus in Marden which caters to students from reception to Year 12 and adults who haven't been able to complete their SACE.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Guardians are also able to apply for their child to be educated from home as long as they provide an education program which meets the same requirements as the Australian Curriculum as well as opportunities for social interaction.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] There are two public universities local to Adelaide, as well as one private university and three constituent colleges of foreign universities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Flinders University of South Australia, Adelaide University and Torrens University Australia—part of the Laureate International Universities are based in Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The University of Adelaide was ranked in the top 150 universities worldwide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Flinders ranked in the top 250 and Uni SA in the top 300.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Torrens University Australia is part of an international network of over 70 higher education institutions in more than 30 countries worldwide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide University is a recent amalgamation between the University of Adelaide and the University of South Australia, ranked in the top 150 globally and top 10 nationally.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Today, it stands as Australia's third-oldest university and a member of the leading "Group of Eight".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The merged university has over 64,000 students and two main campuses on North Terrace, with many other campuses across South Australia, including in Whyalla and Mount Gambier.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The two universities had multiple proposals to merge into a single university.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] A proposal in 2018 failed due to uncertainty as to the new name and leadership of the merged university.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2022, the universities announced a new merger proposal, with the name and leadership issues settled and support from the South Australian government.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Flinders University, with 25,184 students, is based in the southern suburb of Bedford Park, alongside the Flinders Medical Centre, with additional campuses in neighbouring Tonsley and in Victoria Square in the city centre.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2024, the University of the Sunshine Coast opened a new campus in Adelaide where undergraduate and master's courses in ICT and business are offered.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of Divinity is at Brooklyn Park.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] There are several South Australian TAFE (Technical and Further Education) campuses in the metropolitan area that provide a range of vocational education and training.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of the Arts, as a school of TAFE SA, provides nationally recognised training in visual and performing arts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Workers' Educational Association of South Australia (WEA-SA) is an independent not-for-profit adult education organisation based in Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Established in 1913, it is one of Australia's longest running providers of community-based adult learning.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] WEA-SA delivers short courses, lectures, cultural programs, travel and interest clubs designed to promote lifelong learning.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] StudyAdelaide, a collaboration between the South Australian government and the tertiary education sector, maintains an on-line list of schools, universities, and higher education institutions in SA.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In addition to the universities, Adelaide is home to research institutes, including the Royal Institution of Australia, established in 2009 as a counterpart to the two-hundred-year-old Royal Institution of Great Britain.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] While established as a British province, and very much English in terms of its culture, Adelaide attracted immigrants from other parts of Europe early on, including German and other European non-conformists escaping religious persecution.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The first German Lutherans arrived in 1838, bringing with them the vine cuttings that they used to found the acclaimed wineries of the Barossa Valley.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Royal Adelaide Show is an annual agricultural show and state fair, established in 1839 and now a huge event held in the Adelaide Showground annually.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's arts scene flourished in the 1960s and 1970s with the support of successive premiers from both major political parties.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The renowned Adelaide Festival of Arts was established in 1960 under Thomas Playford, which in the same year spawned an unofficial uncurated series of performances and exhibits which grew into the Adelaide Fringe.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Construction of the Adelaide Festival Centre began under Steele Hall in 1970 and was completed under the subsequent government of Don Dunstan, who also established the South Australian Film Corporation in 1972 and the State Opera of South Australia in 1976.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] With the Festival, the Fringe, WOMADelaide, Writers' Week and the Adelaide 500 street motor racing event (along with evening music concerts) all happening in early March, the period became known colloquially as "Mad March".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2014, Ghil'ad Zuckermann founded the Adelaide Language Festival.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] There are many international cultural fairs, most notably the German Schützenfest and Greek Glendi.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide holds an annual Christmas pageant, the world's largest Christmas parade.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] As the state capital, Adelaide has a great number of cultural institutions, many of them along the boulevard of North Terrace.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Art Gallery of South Australia, with about 35,000 works, holds Australia's second largest state-based collection.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adjacent are the South Australian Museum and State Library of South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Botanic Garden, National Wine Centre and Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute are nearby in the East End of the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In the back of the State Library lies the Migration Museum, Australia's oldest museum of its kind.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Further west, the Lion Arts Centre is home to ACE Open, which showcases contemporary art; Dance Hub SA; and other studios and arts industry spaces.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Mercury Cinema and the JamFactory ceramics and design gallery are just around the corner.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Festival Centre (which includes the Dunstan Playhouse, Festival Theatre and Space Theatre), on the banks of the Torrens, is the focal point for much of the cultural activity in the city and home to the State Theatre Company of South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Other live music and theatre venues include the Adelaide Entertainment Centre; Adelaide Oval; Memorial Drive Park; Thebarton Theatre; Adelaide Town Hall; Her Majesty's Theatre; Queen's Theatre; Holden Street Theatres; and the Hopgood Theatre.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Lion Arts Factory, within the Lion Arts Centre, hosts contemporary music in a wide range of genres, as does "The Gov" in Hindmarsh.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The city also has numerous smaller theatres, pubs and cabaret bars which host performances.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2015, it was said that there were now more live music venues per capita in Adelaide than any other capital city in the southern hemisphere, *Lonely Planet* labelled Adelaide "Australia's live music city", and the city was recognised as a "City of Music" by the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Although there were many pubs hosting live music in the CBD in past, the number has slowly diminished.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Grace Emily on Waymouth Street, which was refurbished as a live music venue around 2000, is popular with musicians and patrons alike.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Crown & Anchor ("the Cranker") was saved from demolition in 2024 after a vigorous campaign by the public as well as many musicians and politicians.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] New legislation passed on 11 September 2024 designates the entire Adelaide CBD as a "live music venue area", and gives protection to selected live music venues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In addition to its own WOMAD (WOMADelaide), Adelaide has attracted several touring music festivals, including Creamfields, Laneway, and Groovin' (some since defunct).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has produced musical groups and individuals who have achieved national and international fame.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Noted rocker Jimmy Barnes (formerly lead vocalist with Cold Chisel) spent most of his youth in the northern suburb of Elizabeth.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Australian singer-songwriter Paul Kelly grew up in Adelaide and was head prefect at Rostrevor College.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The first *Australian Idol* winner, Guy Sebastian, hails from the north-eastern suburb of Golden Grove.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] All of the five Australian national television networks broadcast both high-definition digital and standard-definition digital television services in Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] They share three transmission towers on the ridge near the summit of Mount Lofty.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] There are two other transmission sites at 25 Grenfell Street, Adelaide and Elizabeth Downs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The two government-funded stations are run by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC South Australia) and the Special Broadcasting Service (SBS).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Seven Network and Network Ten both own their Adelaide stations (SAS-7 and ADS-10 respectively).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's NWS-9 is part of the Nine Network.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has a community television station, Channel 44.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] As part of a nationwide phase-out of analogue television in Australia, Adelaide's analogue television service was shut down on 2 April 2013.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] There are 20 radio stations that serve the metropolitan area, as well as four stations that serve only parts of the metropolitan area; six commercial stations, six community stations, six national stations and two narrowcast stations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] DAB+ digital radio has been broadcasting in metropolitan Adelaide since 20 May 2009, and currently offers a choice of 41 stations all operated by the existing licensed radio broadcasters, which includes high-quality simulcast of all AM and FM stations.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The main sports played professionally in Adelaide are Australian Rules football, soccer, cricket, netball, and basketball.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the home of two Australian Football League teams: the Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club, and one A-League soccer team, Adelaide United.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] A local Australian rules football league, the South Australian National Football League (SANFL), is made up of 10 teams from around Adelaide.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The SANFL has been in operation since 1877 when it began as the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) before changing its name to the SANFL in 1927.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The SANFL is the oldest surviving football league of any code played in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Since completion of the upgrade, home games for Adelaide Crows and Port Adelaide now take place at Adelaide Oval.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Since 1884, Adelaide Oval has also hosted an international cricket test every summer, along with a number of One Day International cricket matches.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Memorial Drive Park, adjacent to the Adelaide Oval, used to host Davis Cup and other major tennis events, including the Australian Open and the Adelaide International.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's professional association football team, Adelaide United, play in the A-League.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Founded in 2003, their home ground is Coopers Stadium, which has a capacity of 16,500 and is one of the few purpose-built soccer stadia in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Prior to United's foundation, Adelaide City and West Adelaide represented the city in the National Soccer League.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The two sides, which contest the Adelaide derby against one another, now play in the National Premier Leagues South Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] For two years, 1997 and 1998, Adelaide was represented in Australia's top level rugby league, after the New South Wales Rugby League had played a single game per season at the Adelaide Oval for five years starting in 1991.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Rams were formed and played in the breakaway Super League (SL) competition in 1997 before moving to the new National Rugby League in 1998.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Initially playing at the Adelaide Oval, the club moved to the more suitable Hindmarsh Stadium late in the 1998 season.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] As part of a peace deal with the Australian Rugby League to end the Super League war, the club's owners News Limited (who were also owners of the SL) suddenly closed the club only weeks before the start of the 1999 season.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has two professional basketball teams, the men's team being the Adelaide 36ers which plays in the National Basketball League (NBL) and the women's team, the Adelaide Lightning which plays in the Women's National Basketball League (WNBL).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide 36ers play at the Adelaide Entertainment Centre while the Adelaide Lightning play at the Adelaide Arena (Previously Titanium Security Arena).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has a professional netball team, the Adelaide Thunderbirds, which plays in the national netball competition, the Super Netball championship, with home games played at Netball SA Stadium.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Thunderbirds occasionally play games or finals at the Titanium Security Arena, while international netball matches are usually played at the 10,500 seat Adelaide Entertainment Centre.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Titanium Security Arena has a capacity of 8,000 and is the largest purpose-built basketball stadium in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Since 1999 Adelaide and its surrounding areas have hosted the Tour Down Under bicycle race, organised and directed by Adelaide-based Michael Turtur.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Turtur won an Olympic gold medal for Australia in the 4000 m team pursuit at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Tour Down Under is the largest cycling event outside Europe and was the first event outside Europe to be granted UCI ProTour status.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The 2024 Women's Tour Down Under cycle stage race was held in and around Adelaide, South Australia from 12 to 14 January 2024.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide maintains a franchise in the Australian Baseball League, the Adelaide Giants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] They have been playing since 2009, and their home stadium (until 2016) was Norwood Oval.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] From 2016 the team moved to the Diamond Sports Stadium located near the Adelaide International Airport due to renovations at Norwood.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has an ice hockey team, Adelaide Adrenaline in the Australian Ice Hockey League (AIHL).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] It was national champions in 2009 and plays its games at the IceArenA.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Australian Grand Prix for World Championship Formula One racing was hosted by Adelaide from 1985 to 1995 on the Adelaide Street Circuit which was laid out in the city's East End as well as the eastern parklands including the Victoria Park Racecourse.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Grand Prix became a source of pride, and losing the event to Melbourne in a surprise announcement in mid-1993 left a void that has since been filled with the Adelaide 500 for V8 Supercar racing, held on a modified version of the same street circuit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Classic Adelaide, a rally of classic sporting vehicles, is also held in the city and its surrounds.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide formerly had three horse racing venues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Victoria Park, Cheltenham Park Racecourse, both of which have now closed, and Morphettville Racecourse that remains the home of the South Australian Jockey Club.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] It also has Globe Derby Park for Harness racing that opened in 1969, and by 1973 had become Adelaide's premier harness racing venue taking over from the Wayville Showgrounds, as well as Greyhound Park for greyhound racing that opened in 1972.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The World Solar Challenge race attracts teams from around the world, most of which are fielded by universities or corporations, although some are fielded by high schools.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The race has a 20-years' history spanning nine races, with the inaugural event taking place in 1987.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide hosted the 2012 World Bowls Championships at Lockleys Bowling Club, becoming the third city in the world to have held the championships twice, having previously hosted the event in 1996.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Dirt track speedway is also popular in Adelaide with three operating speedways.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Motorsport Park, located adjacent to the Adelaide International Raceway road racing circuit at Virginia (24 km (15 mi) north of the city centre) has been in continuous operation since 1979 after the closure of the popular Rowley Park Speedway.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Gillman Speedway located in the semi-industrial suburb of Gillman, has been in operation since 1998 and caters to Motorcycle speedway and Sidecars, while the Sidewinders Speedway located in Wingfield is also a motorcycle speedway dedicated to Under-16 riders and has been in operation since 1978.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2016, backed by South Australia's Peregrine Corporation opened up a multi-purpose facility; a state-of-the-art motorsporting park and a hotel alongside its newer OTR service station outside a small township of Tailem Bend currently named The Bend Motorsport Park.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Design for thrill seekers and rev-heads the facility currently host South Australia's second Supercars motoring event during a round in August.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is home to the Great Southern Slam, the world's largest roller derby tournament.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The tournament has been held biennially over Australia's Queen's Birthday holiday weekend since 2010.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2014, and 2016 the tournament featured 45 teams playing in two divisions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2018, the tournament has expanded to 48 teams competing in three divisions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Being centrally located on the Australian mainland, Adelaide forms a strategic transport hub for east–west and north–south routes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The city itself has a metropolitan public transport system managed by and known as the Adelaide Metro.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Tramways were largely dismantled in the 1950s, but saw a revival in the 2010s with upgrades and extensions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Road transport in Adelaide has historically been easier than many of the other Australian cities, with a well-defined city layout and wide multiple-lane roads from the beginning of its development.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide was known as a "twenty-minute city", with commuters having been able to travel from metropolitan outskirts to the city proper in roughly twenty minutes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] However, such arterial roads often experience traffic congestion as the city grows.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has one freeway and four expressways.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has two commercial airports, Adelaide Airport and Parafield Airport.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Airport, in Adelaide's south-western suburbs, serves almost 9 million passengers annually, with an extensive number of direct flight routes within Australia, as well as other destinations in Oceania, Asia and North America.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport, Adelaide's second airport 18 kilometres (11 miles) north of the city centre, is used for small aircraft, pilot training and recreational aviation purposes.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport served as Adelaide's main aerodrome until the opening of the Adelaide Airport in February 1955.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also home to a military airport, known as RAAF Base Edinburgh, located in the northern suburbs.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] It was built in 1955 in a joint initiative with the United Kingdom for weapon development.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's two largest hospitals are the Royal Adelaide Hospital (RAH) in Adelaide Parklands, a teaching hospital affiliated with the University of Adelaide (800 beds), and the Flinders Medical Centre (580 beds) at Bedford Park, affiliated with Flinders University.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The RAH also operates additional campuses for specialist care throughout the suburbs including the Hampstead Rehabilitation Centre (150 beds) at Northfield and the Glenside Campus (129 beds) for acute mental health services.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Other major public hospitals are the Women's and Children's Hospital (305 beds), at North Adelaide; the Queen Elizabeth Hospital (340 beds) at Woodville; Modbury Hospital (174 beds) at Modbury; and the Lyell McEwin Hospital (198 beds) at Elizabeth Vale.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Numerous private hospitals are also located throughout the city, with the largest operators being not-for-profits Adelaide Community Healthcare Alliance (three hospitals) and Calvary Care (four hospitals).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2017, the RAH was relocated from the city's East End to a new AU$2.3 billion facility built over former railyards in the West End.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] SAHMRI, with additional external funding, has built a $300 million second facility completed in 2024, which was intended to house the Australian Bragg Centre with Australia's first proton therapy unit.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Construction is underway for the Women's and Children's Hospital to be relocated to the precinct adjacent the RAH by 2030.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The largest provider of community health care within Adelaide is the not-for-profit Royal District Nursing Service, which provides out of hospital care and hospital avoidance care.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's energy requirements were originally met by the Adelaide Electric Supply Company, which was nationalised by the Playford government in 1946, becoming the Electricity Trust of South Australia (ETSA).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The electricity retail market was opened to competition in 2003 and although competition was expected to result in lower retail costs, prices increased by 23.7% in the market's first year.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2004, the privatisation was deemed to be a failure with consumers paying 60% more for their power and with the state government estimated to lose $3 billion in power generation net income in the first ten years of privatisation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2012, the industry came under scrutiny for allegedly reducing supply by shutting down generators during periods of peak demand to force prices up.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Increased media attention also revealed that in 2009 the state government had approved a 46% increase in retail prices to cover expected increases in the costs of generation while generation costs had in fact fallen 35% by 2012.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] South Australia has the highest retail price for electricity in the country.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Privatisation led to competition from a variety of companies who now separately provide for the generation, transmission, distribution and retail sales of gas and electricity.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Electricity generation comes from a range of technologies and operators.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] ElectraNet operates the high-voltage electricity transmission network.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] SA Power Networks distributes electricity to end users.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The largest electricity and gas retailing companies are also the largest generating companies.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The largest fossil fuel power stations are the Torrens Island Power Station gas-fired plant operated by AGL Energy and the Pelican Point Power Station operated by Engie.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has wind and solar power and connections to the national grid.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Gas is supplied from the Moomba Gas Processing Plant in the Cooper Basin via the Moomba Adelaide Pipeline System and the SEAGas pipeline from Victoria.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2011, South Australia generated 18% of its electricity from wind power, and had 51% of the installed capacity of wind generators in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Due to almost universal blackouts within the city during September 2016, the state worked with Tesla to produce the world's largest electricity battery at Hornsdale Power Reserve which has increased that state's electrical security to the extent in which large blackouts are no longer an event.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The provision of water services is by the government-owned SA Water.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's water is supplied from its seven reservoirs: Mount Bold, Happy Valley, Myponga, Millbrook, Hope Valley, Little Para and South Para.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The yield from these reservoir catchments can be as little as 10% of the city's requirements (90GL per annum) in drought years and about 60% in average years.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The remaining demand is met by the pumping of water from the River Murray.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] A sea-water desalination plant capable of supplying 100GL per annum was built during the 2001–2009 drought; however, it operated at about 8% of its capacity until 2019.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In December 2018, the State and Federal Governments agreed to fund a $2m study to determine how the plant could be used to reduce reliance on river water, in an effort to help save the Murray River basin and mouth (including the Coorong) from further ecological damage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] AdelaideFree WiFi is a citywide free Wi-Fi network covering most of the inner city areas of Adelaide, primarily the Adelaide CBD and Northern Adelaide precincts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] It was officially launched at the Adelaide Central Markets on Tuesday 25 June 2014.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] It was originally provided by Internode with infrastructure provided by outdoor Cisco WiFi N access points attached to the top of lighting poles, as well as inside cafes and businesses across the city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2023, a new agreement was reached between the City of Adelaide and TPG Telecom to replace the network infrastructure, improving network speed and coverage.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide, was a 10 sail composite (timber planking on a wrought-iron frame) clipper.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] It was rescued from the mooring where it sank, as HMS Carrick, in Glasgow in 1991.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] In 2001 it was decided that the ship's name would be reverted to the City of Adelaide, formally renamed in 2013, and arrived in Port Adelaide on 3 February 2014.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] It was not until June 2024 that the ship was moved from the barge Bradley by Wallbridge Gilbert Aztec (WGA) to the current home on Dock 2, as the centerpiece of a planned village in Port Adelaide's inner harbour.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The ship is owned by the Clipper Ship City of Adelaide Ltd (CSCOAL).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The STV One and All, a 42-metre two-masted square-rigged brigantine and the ketch *The Failie* are moored at McLaren Wharf.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide has been involved in the sister cities movement since 1972.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] As of 2023 it has long-term international partnership arrangements with five cities, known as sister cities, based on formal agreements between Adelaide and each city.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/adelaide-p02] This allows collaboration in the cultural, educational, business, and technical spheres.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] There are generally distinctive features of phonology, grammar, words and meanings, as well as language use in Australian Aboriginal English, compared with Australian English.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The language is also often accompanied by a lot of non-verbal cues.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Negative attitudes that exist in Australian society towards AbE have negative effects on Aboriginal people across law, health and educational contexts.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Speakers have been noted to tend to change between different forms of AAE depending on whom they are speaking to, e.g. striving to speak more like Australian English when speaking to a non-Aboriginal English-speaking person.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] This is sometimes referred to as diglossia or codeswitching and is common among Aboriginal people living in major cities.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] AAE terms, or derivative terms, are sometimes used by the broader Australian community.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Australian Aboriginal English is spoken among Aboriginal people generally, but is especially evident in what are called "discrete communities", i.e. ex-government or mission reserves such as the DOGIT communities in Queensland.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] There exists a continuum of varieties of Aboriginal English, ranging from light forms, close to standard Australian English, to heavy forms, closer to Kriol.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The varieties developed differently in different parts of Australia, by Aboriginal peoples of many language groups.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Kriol is a totally separate language from English, spoken by over 30,000 people in Australia.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Specific features of Aboriginal English differ between regions.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In Nyungar country in Perth, Western Australia, they include address terms and kinship, uninverted questions (*That's your Auntie?*), the utterance tag *unna*, and Nyungar terms such as *boya*, *boodjar*, *maya-maya*, and *moorditji*, among other features.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Specific terms can be used to refer to local or regional varieties of AbE, for example *Koori* or *Murri English*, *Broome lingo* and *Noongar English*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Nunga English is the southern South Australian dialect of Aboriginal English.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] It includes words from the Narungga, Ngarrindjeri, and West Coast languages, as well as local variations in pronunciation.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] According to Uncle Lewis O'Brien, people from the Point Pearce mission on the Yorke Peninsula have a distinct way of pronouncing "r" in words such as "girl" and "bird", somewhat akin to the accent of the Cornish miners who worked in the area in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Aboriginal English varieties also occur in Indigenous-authored fictional broadcast media, including kinship words like *cousin brother*, *brother boys*, *sister girl* and *daughter girl*, and other frequent words such as *blackfella*(*s*) and *mob*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Similar to Caribbean and African American Vernacular English, Aboriginal English does not make use of auxiliary verbs, such as *to be* and *to have*, or copulas to link things together.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] For example, the Aboriginal English equivalent of "*We are working*" is "*We workin’*".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In Aboriginal English, particularly in northern Australia, the pronouns *he* and *him* may be used for females and inanimate objects in additional to the expected masculine case.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] This is also shared in standard English with the masculine pronouns possessing a neuter case, uncommonly (often historically) referring to an unspecified sex (e.g.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The distinction between *he* as the nominative form and *him* as the oblique form is not always observed, and *him* may be found as the subject of a verb.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Sutton (1989) documents that some speakers of Aboriginal English in the area around Adelaide in South Australia have an uncommon degree of rhoticity, relative to both other AAE speakers and Standard Australian English speakers (which are generally non-rhotic).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] These speakers realise /r/ as [ɹ] in the preconsonantal, postvocalic position (after a vowel and before a consonant), though only within stems.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] For example: [boːɹd] "board", [t̠ʃɜɹt̠ʃ] "church", [pɜɹθ] "Perth"; but [flæː] "flour", [dɒktə] "doctor".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Sutton speculates that this feature may derive from the fact that many of the first settlers in coastal South Australia – including Cornish tin-miners, Scottish missionaries, and American whalers – spoke rhotic varieties.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Many of his informants grew up in Point Pearce and Point McLeay.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Most Australian Aboriginal languages have three- or five-vowel systems, and these form the substrate for Aboriginal English vowel pronunciations, especially in more basilectal accents.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] More basilectal varieties tend to merge a number of vowels, up to the point of merging all Australian English vowels into the three or five vowels of a given speaker's native language.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] That said, the diphthongs, and especially the face and choice diphthongs, tend to be maintained in all but the heaviest accents, albeit they are frequently shortened.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Although Indigenous language and basilectal Aboriginal English vowel systems are small, there is a high degree of allophony.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] For example, vowels may be heavily fronted and raised in the presence of palatal consonants.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Many Aboriginal people, including those who speak acrolectal varieties of English and even those who do not speak an Indigenous language, do not nasalize vowels before nasal consonants, unlike other Australian English speakers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Acrolectal Aboriginal accents tend to have a smaller vowel space compared to Standard Australian English.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The Aboriginal English vowel space tends to share the same lower boundary as Indigenous language vowel spaces, but shares an upper boundary with Standard Australian English, thus representing an expansion upwards from the Indigenous vowel space.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] There are other differences between acrolectal Aboriginal English and Standard Australian English vowel qualities, which tend to represent conservatism on the part of Aboriginal speakers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Balanda is a word used by the Yolŋu people for European people; originally from the Makassarese language, via Malay *orang belanda* (Dutch person).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Aboriginal people (particularly those in the Outback and in the Top End) often refer to themselves and other Aboriginal people as "blackfellas".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The Australian Kriol term for an Aboriginal person is "blackbala", which comes from this term.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The term is considered racist and highly offensive when used by a non-indigenous person.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Many Aboriginal people use the word *business* in a distinct way, to mean "matters".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Funeral and mourning practices are commonly known as "sorry business".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Financial matters are referred to as "money business", and the secret-sacred rituals distinct to each sex are referred to as "women's business" and "men's business".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] "Secret women's business" was at the centre of the Hindmarsh Island Bridge controversy.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Many Aboriginal people refer to their house as their camp, particularly in Central Australia and the Top End of the Northern Territory.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] It can be used to denote a dangerous or aggressive animal or person, so for instance could be used describe a dog that is likely to bite or attack.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The word "country" has special meaning for Aboriginal people; it has a "spiritual and philosophical dimension" by which they relate to a certain place.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Dardy originates in South-western Western Australia and means "cool", or really good.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Deadly is used by many Aboriginal people to mean excellent, or very good, in the same way that "wicked", "sick" or "awesome" is by many young English speakers.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Deadly Awards (aka Deadlys) were awards for outstanding achievement by Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] This usage is not exclusive to Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In some forms of Aboriginal English, "fellow" (usually spelt *fella, feller, fullah, fulla*, etc.) is used in combination with adjectives or numerals, e.g.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] "big fella business" = "important business", "one-feller girl" = "one girl".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] This can give it an adverbial meaning, e.g.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] "sing out big fella" = "call out loudly".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] It is also used with pronouns to indicate the plural, e.g.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] "me fella" = "we" or "us", "you fella" = "you all".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Other words include blackfella (an Aboriginal person) and whitefella (a white person).
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In Victorian era slang used by criminals, "gammon" was to swindle someone or cheat them, used for example in the sense of creating a distraction while pickpocketing; or, more generally, nonsense, "humbug".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Its origin has been variously thought to be related to leg of cured ham known as gammon or the game of backgammon.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The word is used across Australian Aboriginal communities, with its meaning given variously as inauthentic, cheap or broken; to be pretending or joking; or just pathetic or lame.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] *Macquarie Dictionary'*s Australian Word Map ascribes six meanings, based on feedback from around the country, in which the word is used as several different parts of speech, mainly relating to deceit, joking, and false, but also to a lame (pathetic, bad) idea.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] As a verb ("gammon/gamin/gammin around") means to fool around, and may also be used as an expression equivalent to "As if!".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The word is also used by non-Aboriginal people, and it has been noted that the PNG Tok Pisin word for liar is *giaman* or *giamon*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] While it can be used derogatorily, "Gubba" is also used to refer to friends, e.g.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Other words for white people are balanda (see above), migaloo, and wadjela.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The name of the town of Coober Pedy is thought to derive from the Kokatha-Barngarla term *kupa-piti* (or *guba-bidi*), which translates to "whitefellas' hole".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Used in Nunga English (South Australia) to refer to non-Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Whereas humbug in broader English (see Charles Dickens's Scrooge character) means nonsensical, or unimportant information, humbug in Aboriginal English means to pester with inane or repetitive requests.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The Warumpi Band released an album entitled *Too Much Humbug*.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In the Northern Territory, humbug is used by both black and white in this latter, Aboriginal way.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] The most commonly recognised definition of humbug refers to an Aboriginal person asking a relative for money.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Humbugging can become a serious burden where the traditional culture is one of communal ownership and strong obligations between relatives.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Colloquially used to mean a group of Aboriginal people associated with an extended family group, clan group or wider community group, from a particular place or "Country".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] It is used to connect and identify the person and where they are from.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] "My mob" means my people, or extended family.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Mob is often used to refer to a language group, as in "that Warlpiri mob".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Mob and *mobs* are also used to describe a lot of people or things when an actual number is not stated, and is usually associated with "big" or "biggest".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Examples include, "There was a big mob (or the biggest mob) at the football." or "There was no moon, so we could see the biggest mobs of stars" or in a health perspective, "I've got a big mob of pain".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] While "rubbish" as an adjective in many dialects of English means wrong, stupid, or useless, in the north of Australia, "rubbish" is usually used to describe someone who is too old or too young to be active in the local culture.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Another use is meaning something is "not dangerous"; for example, non-venomous snakes are all considered to be "rubbish", while in contrast, venomous snakes are "cheeky".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In both cases, "rubbish" approximately means "inert".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Yarn is an English word for a long story, often with incredible or unbelievable events.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Originally a sailors' expression, "to spin a yarn", in reference to stories told while performing mundane tasks such as spinning yarn.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In Aboriginal English, the word is used as a verb (*yarning*), referring to a "conversational and storytelling style where Indigenous people share stories based on real experience and knowledge, from intimate family gatherings to formal public presentations".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] A "yarning circle" is a way of passing on cultural knowledge and building respectful relationships within a group.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] A 2021 article about Indigenous health communication says that yarning "includes repetition as a way to emphasise what is important in the message", and suggests that using the method can be useful in imparting health information.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] Often conjoined with the word "deadly", "unna" means "True" or "ain't it?".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] It is used primarily by the Nunga (including Ngarrindjeri), Noongar, and Yolngu peoples.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] This word is used frequently in the 1998 novel *Deadly, Unna?* by Phillip Gwynne.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In Aboriginal communities, particularly those in the outback and the Top End, Aboriginal people often refer to white people as "whitefellas".
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] In Australian Kriol, "waitbala" means "a white person" and comes from this word.
[src:australian-aboriginal-english/australian-aboriginal-english] It and its counterpart "blackfella" headline "Blackfella/Whitefella", an Aboriginal country rock anthem about the need for racial harmony.
